<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="330" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,727,1257]" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">
Previous molecular studies suggested that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Henle" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[620,718,727,753]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Brevitrygon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="walga">
<emphasis box="[620,718,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">B. walga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only representative of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Last, Naylor &amp; Manjaji-Matsumoto" authorityYear="2016" box="[1148,1281,727,752]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Brevitrygon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1148,1281,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">Brevitrygon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Persian Gulf and the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[380,448,763,789]" name="Oman" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">Oman</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Naylor, G. J. P. &amp; Caira, J. N. &amp; Jensen, K. &amp; Rosana, K. A. M. &amp; White, W. T. &amp; Last, P. R." box="[462,669,763,789]" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" pagination="1 - 262" refId="ref12031" refString="Naylor, G. J. P., Caira, J. N., Jensen, K., Rosana, K. A. M., White, W. T. &amp; Last, P. R. (2012) A DNA sequence-based approach to the identification of shark and ray species and its implications for global elasmobranch diversity and parasitology. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 367, 1 - 262. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 754.1" type="journal article" year="2012">
Naylor 
<emphasis box="[547,602,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
).Also, the recent revision by 
<bibRefCitation author="Last, P. R. &amp; Naylor, G. J. P. &amp; Manjaji-Matsumoto, B. M." box="[994,1195,763,790]" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" pagination="345 - 368" refId="ref11492" refString="Last, P. R., Naylor, G. J. P. &amp; Manjaji-Matsumoto, B. M. (2016 a) A revised classification of the family Dasyatidae (Chondrichthyes: Myliobatiformes) based on new morphological and molecular insights. Zootaxa, 4139 (3), 345 - 368. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4139.3.2" type="journal article" year="2016">
Last 
<emphasis box="[1048,1103,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">et al.</emphasis>
(2016a)
</bibRefCitation>
remarked that among four species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Last, Naylor &amp; Manjaji-Matsumoto" authorityYear="2016" box="[440,573,799,824]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Brevitrygon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[440,573,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">Brevitrygon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Henle" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[645,744,799,825]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Brevitrygon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="walga">
<emphasis box="[645,744,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">B. walga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[801,941,799,825]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Brevitrygon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="imbricata">
<emphasis box="[801,941,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">B. imbricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are restricted to the Indian Ocean while the first is common in the northwestern part of the region (The Persian Gulf and the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[1139,1209,835,861]" name="Oman" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">Oman</collectingCountry>
) and the last one inhabits western waters of 
<collectingCountry box="[428,486,871,897]" name="India" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">India</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Last, P. R. &amp; White, W. T. &amp; de Carvalho, M. R. &amp; Seret, B. &amp; Stehmann, M. &amp; Naylor, G. J. P." box="[500,693,871,898]" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" refId="ref11561" refString="Last, P. R., White, W. T., de Carvalho, M. R., Seret, B., Stehmann, M. &amp; Naylor, G. J. P. (2016 b) Rays of the World. CSIRO Publishing, Collingwood, 801 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / 9780643109148" type="book" year="2016">
Last 
<emphasis box="[557,612,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">et al.</emphasis>
2016b
</bibRefCitation>
). It seems that some previous reports (
<bibRefCitation author="Henderson, A. C. &amp; Reeve, A. J." box="[1120,1431,871,897]" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" pagination="171 - 175" refId="ref11012" refString="Henderson, A. C. &amp; Reeve, A. J. (2011) Noteworthy elasmobranch records from Oman. African Journal of Marine Science, 33, 171 - 175. https: // doi. org / 10.2989 / 1814232 X. 2011.572380" type="journal article" year="2011">Henderson and Reeve 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Almoji, D. K. &amp; Moore, A. B. M. &amp; White, W. T." box="[151,365,906,933]" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" refId="ref10028" refString="Almoji, D. K., Moore, A. B. M. &amp; White, W. T. (2015) Sharks &amp; rays of the Arabian / Persian Gulf. MBG (INT) Ltd., London, 178 pp." type="book" year="2015">
Almoji 
<emphasis box="[240,298,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
) and sequences deposited in the databases (
<bibRefCitation author="Henderson, A. C. &amp; Reeve, A. J. &amp; Jabado, R. W. &amp; Naylor, G. J. P." box="[869,1129,907,933]" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" pagination="399 - 442" refId="ref11059" refString="Henderson, A. C., Reeve, A. J., Jabado, R. W. &amp; Naylor, G. J. P. (2016) Taxonomic assessment of sharks, rays and guitarfishes (Chondrichthyes. Elasmobranchii) from south-eastern Arabia, using the NADH dehydrogenase subunit 2 (NADH 2) gene. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 176, 399 - 442. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / zoj. 12309" type="journal article" year="2016">
Henderson 
<emphasis box="[1001,1060,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Naylor, G. J. P. &amp; Caira, J. N. &amp; Jensen, K. &amp; Rosana, K. A. M. &amp; White, W. T. &amp; Last, P. R." box="[1142,1354,907,933]" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" pagination="1 - 262" refId="ref12031" refString="Naylor, G. J. P., Caira, J. N., Jensen, K., Rosana, K. A. M., White, W. T. &amp; Last, P. R. (2012) A DNA sequence-based approach to the identification of shark and ray species and its implications for global elasmobranch diversity and parasitology. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 367, 1 - 262. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 754.1" type="journal article" year="2012">
Naylor 
<emphasis box="[1229,1287,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
) might belong to misidentified specimens (Gavin Naylor pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="330" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,727,1257]" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">
Therefore, all materials in our collection were morphologically re-examined. The results revealed that specimens collected from the Persian Gulf and the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[763,831,1015,1041]" name="Oman" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">Oman</collectingCountry>
have up to 12 enlarged thorns on the base of the tail, 2 (n=60) to 3 (n=29) stinging spines, and the denticle band does not cover the trunk area, which is consistent with all diagnostic characteristics of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Henle" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[516,617,1087,1113]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Brevitrygon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="walga">
<emphasis box="[516,617,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">B. walga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. So, the current morphological and molecular (e.g. branch support and genetic distance) evidence support the idea that there is a monophyletic clade and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Henle" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[1079,1178,1123,1149]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Brevitrygon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="walga">
<emphasis box="[1079,1178,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">B. walga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only representative of the genus in the region. Recently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Fernando, D. &amp; Bown, R. M. K. &amp; Tanna, A. &amp; Gobiraj, R. &amp; Ralicki, H. &amp; Jockusch, E. L. &amp; Ebert, D. A. &amp; Jensen, K. &amp; Caira, J. N." box="[606,855,1159,1185]" pageId="14" pageNumber="330" pagination="201" refId="ref10746" refString="Fernando, D., Bown, R. M. K., Tanna, A., Gobiraj, R., Ralicki, H., Jockusch, E. L., Ebert, D. A., Jensen, K. &amp; Caira, J. N. (2019) New insights into the identities of the elasmobranch fauna of Sri Lanka. Zootaxa, 4585 (2), 201. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4585.2.1" type="journal article" year="2019">
Fernando 
<emphasis box="[718,774,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="330">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
reported an unknown taxon that clustered closely to well outside the species. This finding shows that there may be more cryptic species in the genus and more detailed examination should be conducted.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
